# Licensing

AI Safe@Work is dual-licensed:

- **Code** (the contents of `assets/`, `.audit/inject-jsonld.py`, any future scripts, build tooling, and similar machine-readable artefacts) is released under the **MIT License**. See `LICENSE-CODE`.

- **Content** (the contents of every `*.html`, `*.md`, `*.xml`, `*.txt` file that constitutes the course, the standards-map, the templates, the citations, the doctrine, the audit pack — in short, everything that is read by humans rather than executed by machines) is released under **Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-SA 4.0)**. See `LICENSE-CONTENT`.

If you are unsure whether a particular file is code or content, treat it as content (the stricter licence).

## Practical summary

- You may use, copy, modify, and redistribute the material in this repository, for any purpose including commercial.
- For code: include the copyright notice and the MIT licence text.
- For content: attribute "AI Safe@Work" with a link back to the repository, and share derivative works under the same CC BY-SA 4.0 licence.
- Do not strip source acknowledgements.
- Do not pass the work off as your own.
- No warranties — see the relevant licence text for the full disclaimer.

## Why dual

The course is primarily a body of plain-English explanations of regulation. ShareAlike protects it from being absorbed into closed-source corporate training and resold without contribution back. The supporting code (cinematic background, scripts) is small, generic, and useful out of context — MIT keeps friction low.
